Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{for the crumb} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the @chicken thigh{260%g}(diced) and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Fry until golden brown on all sides, ~{5-7%minutes}. Turn every couple of mins. Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @green chilli{1/2}(halved, deseeded and finely chopped) lengthways, deseed then finely chop.

Once the chicken is brown, add the onion to the pan, stir together and cook with the chicken until the onion is soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the garlic, @korma curry paste{50%g} and half the green chilli. Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}, then pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @chicken stock powder{1%tsp} and @water{200%ml}. Stir together.

Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #colander{}, pop half of them in a #bowl{} and roughly mash with a #fork{}. Add the crushed and whole chickpeas to the chicken mixture in the pan. Season with salt and pepper, stir together and bring the mixture to a simmer, reduce the heat to medium and simmer until the mixture has reduced slightly, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @salted peanuts{25%g}(roughly chopped). Pop them in a bowl with the @panko breadcrumbs{25%g} and oil. Season with salt and pepper and mix together. Preheat your #grill{} to high.

Once the sauce has thickened, stir in the @chopped kale{100%g}, cover with a #lid{} and simmer until the kale is tender, ~{5-6%minutes}. Taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it, then pour into an #ovenproof dish{}. Sprinkle over the crumb and grill until the top is golden, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> TIP: Keep an eye on it to make sure it doesn't burn!

Serve the crumble in bowls and sprinkle over the remaining green chilli. Enjoy!